cdi:Activity.cdi:description:
Integrate climate and air quality data with ESS ###############################################
Integrate climate data from ERA5 and air quality data from the EEA with the ESS survey data for Berlin, Oslo, Stockholm, Brussels, London, Prague, Budapest, and Madrid

ERA5 Data (Copernicus) ######################
Ingest and prepare data from ERA5 Data (Copernicus)

EEA Air Quality ###############
Ingest and prepare data from EEA Air Quality

Merging data ############
Merging of ERA 5, EEA and ESS data

cdi:ddiReference.cdi:dataIdentifier: Act 3, Step 1: Merging of ERA 5, EEA and ESS data

cdi:Step.cdi:description:
Get raw input #############
Call public API with GPS coordinates from polygons. You make a call one per month - response file is gridded data, default is Â½ degree lat/long. One month, one region, one variable - 22k - performance is slow (takes a minute) - requires a massive number of calls to collect the data set.

Marshalling data ################
Getting estimated population data - Global Human Settlements data this is Eurostat-based. Merging population data (global human settlements) and ERA5 data and writing to disk (Parquet). Quality checks on merged data by external experts.

Data Processing ###############
Create a date variable from timestamp based on time zone of the region (data is hourly). Account for unit differences (Kelvin to Celcius, meters to millimeters). Group by date (date x variable x region). Temp Average, Max, Min by date; precipitation accumulated by date, wind is max value.. Calculate variables for moving averages (7-day, 30-day, 90-day, 365-day). Remove all data older than 2015. Group (collapse) by region using population-weighted average. NOTE: ERA5 data has some imputed values, some missing values maybe?. In memory: each row is a region: mesh-block per day, regions calculated from this (take average for all values weighted by population of each block). Stored to disk as CSV/SAV, etc. (Data is small enough to be tractable).

Get raw input #############
List of stations with GPS coordinates in a CSV file - pass in selection of stations expressed as GPS coordinates and ID, etc. NUTS regions (valid when data is collected) are described by GPS coordinates (for polygons) If the station is a background station within a region of interest, use the ID to query for that data. For each station and each pollutant, send a query to the API for data from 2001-2022, Return is a list of URLS for CSV files to download. (One year, one pollutant, one station). Pollutants: PM10, PM2.5, O3 (ground-level ozone), NO2, SO2 (these are sibling categories.

Marshalling data ################
5000 CSV-files (from step 1) pulled into one file (EEAStations). Each row is a pollutant-by-station-by-hour. The merged data files is stored (Parquet). This serves as a check-point for external reviewers.

Data Processing ###############
Input is one Parquet file (from step 2). Collapse on time to group by day, using maximums Collapse by region, using maximum Calculate index variables - concentrations used to create classification (Good, Fair, Moderate, etc.) provided by the EEA. Calculate worst quality, number of days with bad quality for different periods, etc. Creating derived variables for these. This is pegged against specific dates (not periods). Store as a file (small enough to be whatever we want). File at station level in Parquet is about 400 MB. Reduced file is 250 k (a 6 MB SPSS file).

Creating date variable ######################
Use variables 'DatetimeBegin' and 'DatetimeEnd' to create variable 'date'.

aqiwdpm10 #########
Compute target variable 'aqiwdpm10' starting from variables 'Concentration' and 'AirPollutant = PM10' for each background station. Compute where 'AirQualityStation' has values for the pollutant. Find max 'Concentration' value for the pollutant for the date. Create EEA Air Quality Index where PM10: 0 to 20 eq 'Good' represented by value '0'; 20 to 40 eq 'Fair' represented by value '1'; 40 to 50 eq 'Moderate' represented by value '2'; 50 to 100 eq 'Poor' represented by value '3'; 100 to 150 eq 'Very Poor' represented by value '4'; 150 to 1200 eq 'Extremely poor' represented by value '5'. Add missing values where data are missing. The worst air quality level measured on a specific date on one of the background stations in the region provides values to the variable.

Merging of ERA 5, EEA and ESS data ##################################
Merge all input files - each respondent is connected to their NUTS region, day of interview - variables added to ESS file. Keep only observations for relevant regions (see coverage). save one integrated file for each ESS round (8, 9 , 9).
